slacker — repository credentials (HTTP Basic authentication)
===========================================================

This directory holds credentials for repositories that require a login
(a private Forgejo/Gitea repo, an authenticated mirror, etc.).

It is OPTIONAL. Public Slackware mirrors need NOTHING here — slacker fetches
them anonymously, exactly as before. Set something up only for a repo that
answers 401/403 without credentials.

Nothing in this directory is created by slacker. You, root, create the files
described below. slacker never writes secrets and never puts them in the
`repos` file, in a log line, or in a printed URL — they travel only in an
`Authorization: Basic` header to the matching repo.


Two ways to provide credentials
-------------------------------

1) NAMED credential set  (recommended, one file per repo)

   Create a file in this directory, e.g.  /etc/slacker/credentials.d/forge :

       username = rizitis
       password = <personal-access-token-or-password>

   Then point the repo at it with the `credentials=` flag on its `repos` line
   (the flag holds only the NAME, never the secret):

       80  myforge  https://forge.slackware.nl/rizitis/myrepo  credentials=forge

   or via the command:

       slacker add-repo 80 myforge https://forge.slackware.nl/rizitis/myrepo credentials=forge


2) GLOBAL catalog  (per-URL, no per-repo flag needed)

   Create  /etc/slacker/credentials.cat  with one section per URL prefix. Any
   repo whose URL begins with a section's prefix uses that section:

       [https://forge.slackware.nl/rizitis]
       username = rizitis
       password = <token>

       [https://private.example.com/repo]
       username = bob
       password = <token>


Lookup order (per repo)
-----------------------

   1. a `credentials=<name>` flag on the repo  -> credentials.d/<name>
   2. else the LONGEST matching prefix in credentials.cat
   3. else the repo is fetched anonymously (the normal case)


File format
-----------

   username = <user>          (`user =` also accepted; `:` works instead of `=`)
   password = <secret>        (`pass =` also accepted)
   # lines beginning with '#' are comments

Named files carry exactly one username/password pair. The catalog carries one
pair per `[url-prefix]` section.


Permissions — REQUIRED
----------------------

slacker REFUSES to read a credential file unless it is:

   * a regular file
   * owned by root  (chown root:root)
   * not readable by group or others  (chmod 600, or stricter like 400)

Anything looser is ignored with a warning, and the repo is fetched
anonymously (fail-safe — a mis-permissioned secret never silently leaks).

Set them up like this:

   chown root:root /etc/slacker/credentials.d/forge
   chmod 600       /etc/slacker/credentials.d/forge

This directory itself should stay root-only (mode 0700) so the file NAMES are
not visible to non-root users.


Notes
-----

* Do NOT put credentials in the URL (https://user:pass@host/...). slacker does
  not support that on purpose — it leaks into logs and the process list.
* A token is preferable to your account password. Create one in your forge
  under Settings -> Applications, with read (package/repo) scope only.
* Credentials live under /etc (admin-managed config), not in the disposable
  cache. Remember they are included if you back up /etc.
